******
[7] Vermont (Grand Isle and Chittenden Counties): wild birds
Date: Fri 8 Apr 2022
Source: WCAX [edited]
https://www.wcax.com/2022/04/08/deadly-strain-avian-flu-found-vermont/


A deadly strain of bird flu sweeping through flocks around the country is in Vermont.

At least 2 bald eagles were found dead and tested positive for avian influenza, known as bird flu.

The eagles were found in Grand Isle and Chittenden counties near Lake Champlain.

Bird flu has been spreading across the country, and it has hit the Green Mountain State.

The CDC says the risk to the general public from this strain is low.

David Mears of Audubon Vermont says we need to learn more before we know how much of a risk this will be to bird populations here.

"It's too soon to know but definitely of concern. We just recently recovered the bald eagle from the endangered status, we don't want to see it go back that direction. But it's of significant concern to the poultry industry," Mears said.

A concern, but it's important to note there are no confirmed cases in poultry in Vermont.

The state says the virus is often initially introduced to domestic poultry by infected wild birds, through direct contact or contact with their droppings.

The state adds anyone involved with poultry, from the small backyard coop to the large commercial producer, should review their biosecurity activities to ensure the health of their birds.

Areas where birds congregate are a concern, so Audubon Vermont wants you to take down your bird feeders now. You're supposed to anyway to avoid attracting bears.

If you see any dead birds, not just bald eagles, the state wants to hear from you. Report sick birds or unusual bird deaths to the USDA or Vermont authorities through USDA's toll-free number as soon as possible.

[Byline: Ike Bendavid]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Mahmoud Orabi

[As one can see, the cases of highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) H5N1 are spreading rapidly across North America. This disease is extremely contagious among birds and spreads very rapidly. It is resulting in the destruction of millions upon millions of birds. It is devastating to producers, to owners, regardless of the size of their operation or their back yard birds. The disease does not discriminate regarding size of flocks or species of birds.

It is critical to protect your birds. Bring them inside. Then practice biosecurity with a consciousness of protecting the birds. Before you go into any bird area, be sure to have on clean boots (that have never been used around other birds), clean scrubs/coveralls, hair nets, gloves, and by all means blow your nose before you enter the facility. While this may seem like a lot, the safety of the birds, yours or someone else's, should make it worthwhile. - Mod.TG


